entry.title: her second studio album (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that English singer Ella Henderson (pictured) almost named her second studio album Chapter Two, but decided instead that "this is a whole book"?

entry.title: Distomus variolosus (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that the sea squirt Distomus variolosus colonises both fronds of kelp and the shells of crustaceans such as the spider crab Maja brachydactyla?

entry.title: Daisy Wood Hildreth (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ...that "The College Chimes" by American composer Daisy Wood Hildreth was chosen by the Iowa State College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts as their alumni song?

entry.title: otomechikku (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that otomechikku, a subgenre of Japanese girls' comics focusing on stories about ordinary teenaged protagonists, has been compared to monogatari and the genre of Bildungsroman?

entry.title: Free Comic Book Day (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Free Comic Book Day was inspired by Free Scoop Night at an ice cream parlor?

entry.title: Visitor (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that although it spent only one week on the Hot Rock & Alternative Songs chart, "Visitor" was the fifth Adult Alternative Airplay number-one for Of Monsters and Men?

entry.title: Vincent Munier (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Vincent Munier's quest to photograph snow leopards became the basis for several books and a film?

entry.title: Doug (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Doug was nominated to Guinness World Records as the world's largest potato before genetic testing confirmed that it was actually a tuber of a gourd?
